   <h1>Re: [VB] 6 volt to 12 volt conversion, is it that easy?</h1>
   <b>"56 vert" <droptop56(-at-)hotmail.com></b><br/>
   <i>2002-03-07 18:25:56+00</i><br/>
   <br/>
   <pre>I actually took a grinder to my housing in one of my bus conversions.  You 
should have seen the sparks fly....  Must have been the magnesium.


>From: Denis Dodson 
>To: jbakerccymca(-at-)springmail.com
>CC: vintagebus 
>Subject: Re: [VB]  6 volt  to 12 volt conversion, is it that easy?
>Date: Thu, 07 Mar 2002 07:08:49 -0800
>
>I'm going to try to remember all the crap I leaned and pass it on, so you
>guys out there who really know your stuff be kind in your corrections.
>
>Is your transmission the original (6 volt)? If it is you will have to cut
>some clearance in the bell housing. This is not hard to do. If you put in
>the engine and hook up the electrical, take the wire off the coil so it
>won't start, put in the bolts just a little, turn the engine over just a
>little. The hard steel flywheel will cut into the soft metal of the bell
>housing and show you where to cut. You can actually continue to tighten,
>turn the engine and cut the metal to compltion, but that made me nervous.
>You will also need a special bushing on the starter. It is thicker than the
>standard 6volt one. A 12 volt starter for an automatic will eliminate that
>hassle.
>
>Did I do right, guys?
>
>----- Original Message -----
>From: "John Baker" 
>To: "Thom Fitzpatrick" 
>Cc: ; 
>Sent: Thursday, March 07, 2002 6:45 AM
>Subject: [VB] 6 volt to 12 volt conversion, is it that easy?
>
>
> > Thanks Thom.  So, let me see if if I understand the article.  My 12 Volt
>engine is turnkey complete, so it already has a 12 volt generator (or is it
>alternator?), coil, and choke, no problem there.  So according to the info,
>I should be able to put the 6 volt flywheel and clutch onto the 12 volt
>engine, then simply put the engine into the 1966 bus and use existing 6 
>volt
>starter and bell housing configuration and operate the bus off of a 12 volt
>power source?  That seems WAY too easy, am I missing something?  What about
>voltage regulator, that would have to be change to a 12 Volt, right?
>Obviously all bulbs, relays, etc would need to be switched over, but there
>has got to be something I'm not thinking of, otherwise it's too simple!
> > Thanks, John Baker
> >
> >
> > On Wed, 6 Mar 2002 19:50:26 -0800 (PST) Thom Fitzpatrick 
>
>wrote:
> >
> > Go to: http://www.vintagebus.com/howto
> >
> > John Baker wrote:
> > > OK, I have a good 12 Volt 1600 Dp engine which I want to put into a 6
>volt 66 Kombi. Can I really just take the 6 volt flywheel and put it on the
>12 volt engine?  What else would need to be changed out?  Voltage 
>Regulator,
>Bulbs, Wiper motor?
> > >
> > >
> > >
> > > Peace, John Baker
> > > 1971 Westy
> > > 1966 Kombi
> > > http://www.geocities.com/jbakerccymca
> > > "...so we got in the red VW microbus with the shovels and rakes and
>implements of destruction and
> > > headed on to the police officer's station..."
